Example SWOT for a mid-size B2B SaaS: Strengths — strong NPS, vertical expertise; Weaknesses — slow onboarding, weak analytics; Opportunities — mid-market expansion, AI features; Threats — well-funded entrant, pricing pressure. Translation principle: each SWOT cell maps to SO/WO/ST/WT moves, then to dated objectives with owners and metrics. Days 1–30 (diagnose & stabilize): WO — cut time-to-first-value from 21 to 10 days by rewriting the onboarding checklist and assigning a CSM owner (Owner: VP CS, KPI: median TTFV); ST — publish a competitive battlecard vs. the new entrant and retrain AEs (Owner: PMM, KPI: win-rate in contested deals). Days 31–60 (build & differentiate): SO — ship an AI-assisted reporting MVP to 10 design-partner accounts leveraging vertical data (Owner: Head of Product, KPI: 7 of 10 active weekly); SO — launch a vertical thought-leadership campaign (Owner: CMO, KPI: 150 MQLs from target ICP). Days 61–90 (scale & defend): WO — replace the analytics module's top three gaps identified from MVP feedback (Owner: Eng Lead, KPI: feature parity score ≥ 0.9); WT — introduce a value-based pricing tier to blunt discounting pressure (Owner: CFO + CRO, KPI: ASP up 8%, discount depth down 5 pts). Governance: weekly 30-minute exec review against a single dashboard (TTFV, win-rate, MQLs, MVP activation, ASP), with a stop/continue decision at day 45 and a 90-day retrospective feeding the next cycle. Risks & guardrails: cap AI MVP spend at $250k, freeze scope after day 45, and pre-commit to sunsetting any initiative missing 70% of its KPI by day 75.
